The secretary Dionisio Pérez Jácome announces details about the airplane accident in which the government secretary Francisco Blake and other seven people died.
The Secretaría de Comunicaciones Y of transport - SCT (secretariat for communication and transport in Mexico) informed that the investigation results about the accident with which the government secretary Francisco Blake Mora and other seven people died point out to the fact that the helicopter with his whole unscathed structure has banged directly into the ground, without the pilot could have initiated an emergency landing.
With a press conference Dionisio Pérez Jácome, secretary mentioned for communication and transport that the pilot had confirmed before the start, the weather terms have been suitable for the flight.
"The circumstances that the air-screw wings had at 25-metre height of contact with trees and the helicopter lost the body seem to point out to the fact that the helicopter had had several ground contacts."
He also explained that the helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why he fulfilled all conditions for the transport of the staff.
Moreover, he said that no helicopter parts were found with the investigations in the area on which the machine had come down.
"No airplane parts were found with the search at other places, the impact concerned the whole structure.
The helicopter was built for 19 passengers, which is why he fulfilled all conditions for the personal transport.
The area shows a Schrägung of 7 to 30 degrees.
At the moment it is priority to get the investigation results as soon as possible, indeed, even one year can last these several months, maybe.
On his part Gilberto López Meyer, general manager of Aeropuertos assured of Y Servicios Auxiliares (secretariat for airplanes and auxiliary services in Mexico) that the helicopter of the Estado mayor Presidencial had flown with the impact with travel airspeed and the airplane on a soft slope had liked.
"This information strengthens the acceptance that it concerned at the time of the impact a normal flight operation."
With a press conference the leader of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, enumerated six relevant points which should be considered with the investigation:
View flight:
In the harmony with the flight norms it concerned a flight under the rules of the view flight. This means that the team would have to have had sufficient view during the flight and on the ground.
Weather terms:
The AICM registered suitable weather terms by the start. During the continuation in the direction of the border area between Mexico town and the Mexico state some deeply hanging clouds gathered.
Elective flight routes:
It is possible that the team had selected a lower area with better view in the direction of the Cuernavaca valley because of the clouds.
Impact place:
The impact co-ordinates and the last radar recording of the helicopter agree. Possibly there has been before the impact neither a controlling loss over the airplane nor a divergence of the flight route.
Verstreuung of the remains of the airplane in a restricted area:
The information being up to the current time points to the fact that the helicopter from straight and lateral direction had hit.
The pattern of the scattered airplane leftovers let assume that the helicopter with his unscathed structure had hit the ground.
No tips to fire or explosion:
The remains of the airplane offer at the accident place conclude neither by fire nor by explosion.
The last investigation results point to several ground contacts.
Airplane parts on a height of 9200 foot about the sea level were found with the investigations on site. The area is sloping and shows a Schrägung of from seven to thirty degrees.
The photos show the sequence in which the helicopter has probably got broken.
Some information points to the fact that the helicopter could have had several ground contacts.
After a minuziösen search in an area which went out the barred area at the accident place no scattered airplane parts could be found what strengthens the acceptance that the unscathed airplane structure had banged into the ground.
